\pard\f0\fs28    {\b 3. C. longus} L., {\i Sp. Pl}. 45 (1753) ({\i Pycreus longus} (L.) Hayek; incl. {\i C. badius} Desf.). Perennial; rhizomes long, 3-10 mm wide, knotted, covered with broad scales; tubers absent; stems 20-150 cm, solitary. Leaves 2-10 mm wide, shorter than to equalling the stems. Bracts 2-6, the outer exceeding the inflorescence. Inflorescence a simple or compound umbel; rays 2-10, up to 35 cm. Spikelets 4-25(-60)x 1-2 mm, linear to oblong, with 6-32 flowers, ascending to patent. Rhachilla broadly winged. Glumes 2-3 × 1·5-2 mm, ovate or elliptical, obtuse, dark brown or reddish with greenish keel. Stamens 3. Nut 1/3-3/4 as long as the glumes, brownish to black.{\i  S., W. & C. Europe, northwards to S. England.} Al Au Az Bl Br Bu Co Cr Ga †Ge Gr He Hs Hu It Ju Lu Rm Rs (K, E) Sa Si Tu.
\par

\par

\pard\f0\fs28   Variable in length of stems, rays and spikelets, width of leaves, and number of bracts and rays. Variants having 2-5 rays which are up to 5 cm long and spikelets 4-12 mm, which occur almost throughout the European range of the species, have been named subsp.{\b  badius} (Desf.) Murb.,{\i  Contr. Fl. Nord-Ouest Afr.}{\b  3}: 27 (1899) ({\i Pycreus badius} (Desf.) Hayek), but intermediates are frequent and the plants in question are worth no more than varietal rank.
